title: fanoutqa: Who were the Nobel Laureates in Literature from 2010 to 2015, and what are the titles of their most famous works? (4c66f78757f3863f)

chat_history.content: Who were the Nobel Laureates in Literature from 2010 to 2015, and what are the titles of their most famous works?

Here are the Nobel Laureates in Literature from 2010 to 2015 along with the titles of some of their most renowned works:
1. 2010: Mario Vargas Llosa (Peru) - Known for novels such as *The Time of the Hero* (*La ciudad y los perros*, 1963), *Aunt Julia and the Scriptwriter* (*La tía Julia y el escribidor*, 1977), and *The Feast of the Goat* (*La fiesta del chivo*, 2000).
2. 2011: Tomas Tranströmer (Sweden) - A celebrated poet, some of his notable works include *Windows and Stones* (*Sjöängen*, 1954), *The Half-Finished Heaven* (*Den halvfärdiga himlen*, 1962), and *The Great Enigma: New Collected Poems* (1996).
3. 2012: Mo Yan (China) - Author of *Red Sorghum* (*Hong gaoliang jiazu*, 1986), *The Garlic Ballads* (*Suan nian hua*, 1988), and *Frog* (*Wa*, 2009).
4. 2013: Alice Munro (Canada) - Renowned for her short stories, some collections include *The Moons of Jupiter* (1982), *Open Secrets* (1994), and *Runaway* (2004).
5. 2014: Patrick Modiano (France) - His novels often explore themes of memory and identity, with notable works including *La Place de l'Étoile* (1968), *Missing Person* (*Rue des Boutiques Obscures*, 1978), and *Dora Bruder* (1997).
6. 2015: Svetlana Alexievich (Belarus) - A journalist and non-fiction writer, her books include *The Unwomanly Face of War* (*Unikam i ne zhenshchin, 1985), *Voices from Chernobyl: The Oral History of a Nuclear Disaster* (*Chernobylskaya molitva*, 1997), and *Second-Hand Time* (*Vtorichnoe vremya: kelst i voiny posle SSSR*, 2013).
